There are 800 over-the-counter pediatric cough and cold products.
Most over-the-counter cold and cough medicines have been tested in children.
Makers continued to sell cough and cold products labeled for infants.
Indeed a growing number of studies suggest that cough and cold medicines work no better in children than placebos.
Common children cold and cough medicines are coming under scrutiny from federal drug regulators.
Many cold and cough drugs won FDA approval decades ago when the agency standards were less strict.
The review covers medicines that include decongestants antihistamines cough suppressants and expectorants.

